WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.050 --> 00:00:02.020
ADAM STEWART: Welcome to
Musicians at Google.

00:00:02.020 --> 00:00:04.640
I am Adam Stewart, and
I'm very proud to

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:06.240
introduce John Taylor.

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:10.070
John is the bass player of Duran
Duran, founding member

00:00:10.070 --> 00:00:12.000
of the iconic British band that
was actually referred to

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.480
as the Fab Five.

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:15.350
So if you're going to get a
compliment, get compared to

00:00:15.350 --> 00:00:17.410
the Fab Four, for sure.

00:00:17.410 --> 00:00:19.600
John's book came out on
Tuesday the 16th.

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:22.850
"In the Pleasure Groove: Love,
Death, and Duran Duran." I

00:00:22.850 --> 00:00:24.540
highly recommend the book.

00:00:24.540 --> 00:00:26.720
The book has been the best
seller in the UK, where it was

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:28.080
released a couple weeks ago.

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:29.590
Currently number six
on the New York

00:00:29.590 --> 00:00:31.350
Times bestseller list.

00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:33.160
So what we're going to do today
is John and I will talk

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:35.020
a little bit, and then John's
also going to read a couple

00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:37.180
passages from the books.

00:00:37.180 --> 00:00:39.610
John will stay afterwards to
sign a book, so they're

00:00:39.610 --> 00:00:41.410
sitting outside, so please
be sure to get

00:00:41.410 --> 00:00:42.860
a copy of the book.

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:44.210
And just a couple of requests.

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:47.370
We ask no flash photography
or recording, and

00:00:47.370 --> 00:00:48.480
if you could, everyone--

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:50.140
I know this is hard to
do at Google-- please

00:00:50.140 --> 00:00:52.810
silence your phones.

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:57.570
John, 1978 was the year that
Duran Duran was formed, and

00:00:57.570 --> 00:01:00.090
you have an amazing career.

00:01:00.090 --> 00:01:02.906
What made you decide to
write the book at this

00:01:02.906 --> 00:01:04.610
point in your life?

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:07.480
JOHN TAYLOR: A couple
of things.

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:10.890
On the one hand, I lost my dad
coming up on three years ago

00:01:10.890 --> 00:01:14.030
this Christmas, and he passed
away in the house

00:01:14.030 --> 00:01:15.380
that I grew up in.

00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:22.140
And I sold the house, drove away
from the neighborhood.

00:01:22.140 --> 00:01:23.850
He was the last of
his generation.

00:01:27.635 --> 00:01:32.100
I mean, I live in the fast lane,
like all of us here, and

00:01:32.100 --> 00:01:35.780
I find that constantly, I have
to really fight to hold onto

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:38.600
my memory these days, because
there's so much information

00:01:38.600 --> 00:01:39.150
coming at me.

00:01:39.150 --> 00:01:44.340
And I found that from the moment
my dad was buried, the

00:01:44.340 --> 00:01:46.960
forgetting what was happening
so quickly.

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:51.160
And so that kind of motivated
me to think about

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:54.080
memorializing my parents
in some way.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:56.990
I wasn't quite sure what that
was going to be, but I'm an

00:01:56.990 --> 00:01:59.210
artist, so it's natural.

00:01:59.210 --> 00:02:02.092
I was thinking, should I
write some songs, or--

00:02:02.092 --> 00:02:03.750
I didn't know what it
was going to be.

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:06.620
And then I was approached,
actually, at the

00:02:06.620 --> 00:02:07.790
beginning of last year.

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:11.070
There's been quite a boom in
music memoirs in the last

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:11.610
couple years.

00:02:11.610 --> 00:02:14.695
We've got Keith Richards
to thank for that.

00:02:14.695 --> 00:02:18.410
And I was approached by an agent
in London who said, if

00:02:18.410 --> 00:02:22.350
you were to be interested in
writing a book, this would be

00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:23.120
a really good time.

00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:26.660
And I thought, well, maybe
that's what it is.

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:29.720
So I kind of started formulating
the idea for the

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:31.490
book, which is kind
of in three parts.

00:02:31.490 --> 00:02:34.960
There's growing up in the '60s
in the Midlands of England and

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:37.480
becoming John.

00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:42.010
And then the second section of
the book's hysteria, and

00:02:42.010 --> 00:02:46.100
that's really about the first
five years of the '80s and

00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:47.850
this wild ride that
Duran Duran took.

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:49.940
And then the third part of the
book is the bit I call

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:54.480
becoming an adult human being,
and that's really been some of

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:57.180
the more profound highlights
of the

00:02:57.180 --> 00:02:59.690
last 15 years, I suppose--

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:04.440
losing parents, gaining
children, marriages, divorces,

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:05.950
all of that sort of stuff.

00:03:05.950 --> 00:03:10.130
Real life stuff, but through
the lens of an ex-pop star.

00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:15.010
ADAM STEWART: Could you talk a
little bit about your process

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:15.510
for the book?

00:03:15.510 --> 00:03:17.960
I know you partnered with Tom
Sykes, and Tom's a freelance

00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:20.710
journalist, "Men's Health,"
"GQ," a bunch of other

00:03:20.710 --> 00:03:22.230
publications.

00:03:22.230 --> 00:03:27.080
And at the same time, you're
going back 30 plus years, and

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:28.890
you've got all of these things,
and the book really

00:03:28.890 --> 00:03:31.790
kind of tells a chronological
story, as you mentioned.

00:03:31.790 --> 00:03:33.300
So how did that all
come together?

00:03:33.300 --> 00:03:38.220
JOHN TAYLOR: Well, when I did
move everything out of my

00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:43.780
parents' house, I did come
out with a dozen boxes of

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:48.730
memorabilia from my early life,
which I thought a lot of

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:50.380
it was just gold.

00:03:50.380 --> 00:03:53.550
I thought, wow, I've got to
use this for something.

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:55.950
So I knew that I was
going to have some

00:03:55.950 --> 00:03:57.910
really, really good evidence.

00:03:57.910 --> 00:04:00.580
I had to sift through that,
and sort of organize it.

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:03.500
Tom Sykes, you mentioned, he's
the ghost writer on the book,

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:05.040
and he was fantastic.

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:07.440
I don't think I could have
done it without him.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:09.860
I thanked him in the back of the
book for holding the torch

00:04:09.860 --> 00:04:12.510
steady as we went through
the attics.

00:04:12.510 --> 00:04:17.019
And he just kept me rolling.

00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:20.589
We couldn't descend
into neuroses.

00:04:20.589 --> 00:04:25.330
Once we made the decision to do
it, and we had a schedule,

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:26.470
and we had to stick to it.

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:29.200
And there was a couple of times
I thought, what am I

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:29.940
doing this for?

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:32.000
I knew I was going to have
to get into some

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:33.540
kind of murky stuff.

00:04:33.540 --> 00:04:35.990
It wasn't all going
to be happy.

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:40.570
But I felt that for the book
to have any sense of

00:04:40.570 --> 00:04:45.800
authenticity to it, it was going
to have to touch on some

00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:50.330
of the darker sides
of success.

00:04:50.330 --> 00:04:54.700
But yeah, we had a pretty good
working ethic, and when things

00:04:54.700 --> 00:04:57.400
got really tough, we'd just get
on our bikes and go for a

00:04:57.400 --> 00:04:59.800
ride, burn it off.

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:00.910
ADAM STEWART: Sources
of inspiration

00:05:00.910 --> 00:05:01.640
while you were writing.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:02.850
Were you going back
and listening

00:05:02.850 --> 00:05:03.625
to some of the music?

00:05:03.625 --> 00:05:05.120
Were you reading something
in particular?

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:07.890
I know you mentioned Keith's
book, although I think your

00:05:07.890 --> 00:05:10.800
book takes a different tone,
because Keith dishes a lot on

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:11.440
his bandmates.

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:13.670
And you didn't necessarily
take that tactic.

00:05:13.670 --> 00:05:14.630
JOHN TAYLOR: Well, I've
read a lot of books.

00:05:14.630 --> 00:05:16.380
I've read a lot of books.

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:20.180
I'm a huge fan, first, of
popular culture, so I've read

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:23.670
a lot of books over the years.

00:05:23.670 --> 00:05:26.640
And generally, the better books
about music are written

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:28.550
by writers.

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:32.020
But there are one or two memoirs
that really work.

00:05:32.020 --> 00:05:34.650
I mean, actually, I remember
when I was about 14, Ian

00:05:34.650 --> 00:05:36.890
Hunter, who was the singer with
Mott the Hoople, and he

00:05:36.890 --> 00:05:40.440
wrote this book called "Diary of
a Rock and Roll Star." And

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:45.920
it was a very pragmatic, day
by day breakdown of what a

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:49.850
band did when it was on
the road in America.

00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:51.710
It wasn't a sex, drugs, and
rock and roll thing.

00:05:51.710 --> 00:05:53.420
It was just really basic.

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:59.690
But to me, wow, it was just so
glamorous and evocative.

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:04.020
I mean, it was all about
finding a voice.

00:06:04.020 --> 00:06:08.170
I mean, I guess I've done enough
blogging, and I've done

00:06:08.170 --> 00:06:13.700
enough interviews to know that
when I'm in the mood, I can

00:06:13.700 --> 00:06:15.220
tell a story well.

00:06:15.220 --> 00:06:19.420
It's just finding the way to
put that down to actually

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:21.180
record that in the computer.

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:25.580
And once we got the right
attitude, the right tempo, it

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:27.540
all started to flow.

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:29.400
ADAM STEWART: What do you think
might be the biggest

00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:32.980
surprise for someone who
picks up the book?

00:06:32.980 --> 00:06:34.560
JOHN TAYLOR: I think there's a
number of surprises in there.

00:06:37.690 --> 00:06:39.530
I mean, it's not just
about fame.

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:41.230
It's not just about,
well, we did this,

00:06:41.230 --> 00:06:42.020
and then we did that.

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:45.920
It's a very personal,
very human account.

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:50.710
Frank is a word that is used
to describe it a lot.

00:06:50.710 --> 00:06:57.320
I mean, it's a coming of age
book, in a way, and I was able

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:01.460
to disconnect from the character
quite a bit, really,

00:07:01.460 --> 00:07:06.520
because just watching this
little kid, an only child,

00:07:06.520 --> 00:07:10.410
mother raging Catholicholic took
him to church every day

00:07:10.410 --> 00:07:14.180
of his life for the first
five years, and

00:07:14.180 --> 00:07:15.420
how he got into music.

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:17.810
How music just took
over for him.

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:23.630
But I mean, I didn't have the
kind of parents that made me

00:07:23.630 --> 00:07:25.380
take piano lessons.

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:29.460
My parents were completely
clueless when it came to

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:31.890
school and education.

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:33.305
I had to find it for myself.

00:07:36.230 --> 00:07:41.160
And it was at that time, 12,
13, 14, where the desire to

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:46.630
remake my identity was so
strong, and music at that time

00:07:46.630 --> 00:07:49.310
in the UK--

00:07:49.310 --> 00:07:50.550
we were talking about
this earlier--

00:07:50.550 --> 00:07:52.840
I mean, there were a lot
of very, very strong

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:53.580
personalities.

00:07:53.580 --> 00:07:56.870
David Bowie, Freddie Mercury,
Rod Stewart, Bryan Ferry.

00:07:56.870 --> 00:07:58.530
I mean, these guys
coming out--

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:00.740
I mean, I'm not going to say was
a golden age, but it was a

00:08:00.740 --> 00:08:03.640
very strong age in terms
of personalities.

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:08.280
And for a kid that was just
not really connecting in

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:13.365
school, was an only child, I
just started connecting with

00:08:13.365 --> 00:08:14.480
these guys in a big way.

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:16.870
And even though I couldn't play
an instrument, I just

00:08:16.870 --> 00:08:18.720
wanted to be in that club.

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:22.630
And so by the time I was
17, I knew that's

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:24.550
what I wanted to do.

00:08:24.550 --> 00:08:26.330
ADAM STEWART: So your career is
really amazing, and I think

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:28.630
when people look at a career
like yours, they think--

00:08:28.630 --> 00:08:29.840
there's probably three things.

00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:33.630
Is it luck, is it timing,
or is it hard work?

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:33.840
JOHN TAYLOR: Yeah.

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:37.919
Well, I think also, part of the
book is demystifying that.

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:41.270
I mean, a lot of collaborators,
people come and

00:08:41.270 --> 00:08:44.020
they work with us, and they're
looking for the magic.

00:08:44.020 --> 00:08:46.796
They're looking for how did you
guys-- what do you guys--

00:08:46.796 --> 00:08:47.210
what's the thing?

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:49.530
And it's like, you
just show up.

00:08:49.530 --> 00:08:51.220
You just show up at the
studio and start

00:08:51.220 --> 00:08:52.470
hitting chords around.

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:57.750
I mean, I was humbled, actually,
looking at the--

00:08:57.750 --> 00:09:02.950
I really got into the first few
years of the '80s, because

00:09:02.950 --> 00:09:05.870
apart from the fact it was a
fantastic time to be in Duran

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:08.840
Duran, I think it was a really
great time for pop culture,

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:11.900
and a very under-appreciated
time in the culture.

00:09:11.900 --> 00:09:13.760
I mean, maybe we'll start
looking at it more as the

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:14.960
beginning of techno.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:20.260
It was the period when fashion,
photography, video,

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:23.940
things were starting to connect
in music in a more

00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:25.510
formal way.

00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:28.140
It was a renaissance
time, in a way.

00:09:28.140 --> 00:09:30.120
And I really wanted
to look at that.

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:32.500
And I don't write about
it in any great

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:34.620
depth, but it's there.

00:09:34.620 --> 00:09:37.300
I was humbled by the amount
of work we did, man.

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:37.790
Oh my god.

00:09:37.790 --> 00:09:41.490
I mean, the funniest thing,
actually-- it was 1982, which

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:47.400
was the year of "Rio." And we
were in the studio in London,

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:49.590
I think, for about two,
maybe three months

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:51.830
recording that album.

00:09:51.830 --> 00:09:56.050
And we came out of Air Studios
and flew straight to Sri

00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:58.800
Lanka, where we did videos for
"Hungry Like The Wolf," and

00:09:58.800 --> 00:09:59.800
"Save A Prayer."

00:09:59.800 --> 00:10:01.870
We went from there to Australia
for our first time,

00:10:01.870 --> 00:10:03.470
and Australia was like
Beatlemania.

00:10:03.470 --> 00:10:05.660
And then we went from there
to Japan, which was like

00:10:05.660 --> 00:10:08.680
Beatlemania but with
Japanese accents.

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:09.220
Madness!

00:10:09.220 --> 00:10:09.495
Madness!

00:10:09.495 --> 00:10:12.310
And then we came to America, and
America, obviously, is a

00:10:12.310 --> 00:10:14.610
very hard territory to break.

00:10:14.610 --> 00:10:15.660
Very, very hard.

00:10:15.660 --> 00:10:17.450
And that summer, we really
went for it.

00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:20.800
We crisscrossed the country
several times.

00:10:20.800 --> 00:10:24.620
Fortunately, at the time, our
record company, Capital, was

00:10:24.620 --> 00:10:26.740
being controlled by
the London office.

00:10:26.740 --> 00:10:29.120
There are no American record
labels like that anymore.

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:31.980
So the London office was kicking
their asses every day

00:10:31.980 --> 00:10:34.230
saying, you've got to break
this band, or we're

00:10:34.230 --> 00:10:35.020
going to lose them.

00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:38.070
So Capital were like, OK,
OK, what do we do?

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:41.930
And it was a massive campaign.

00:10:41.930 --> 00:10:44.110
MTV started happening
at the same time.

00:10:44.110 --> 00:10:48.490
We were seeing our ticket sales
and album sales were

00:10:48.490 --> 00:10:52.250
coming up in states that
MTV was showing in.

00:10:52.250 --> 00:10:54.150
We went back to Europe.

00:10:54.150 --> 00:10:59.990
We did a victory lap of Britain
at the end of the

00:10:59.990 --> 00:11:05.480
year, like November, House
Records in our home city.

00:11:05.480 --> 00:11:07.870
And then I'm looking, and I've
got all this out, and I've got

00:11:07.870 --> 00:11:10.570
the itineraries from back there,
and I see that we're at

00:11:10.570 --> 00:11:14.952
the Holiday Inn in Birmingham
on December 1, 1982, and I'm

00:11:14.952 --> 00:11:17.390
thinking, OK, so what
happens then.

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:20.710
After all of this, oh, I go
back to my parents' house,

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:22.890
because I'm still living
with my parents.

00:11:22.890 --> 00:11:24.152
That's how crazy--

00:11:24.152 --> 00:11:26.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:28.480
JOHN TAYLOR: But it happened
so fucking fast.

00:11:31.310 --> 00:11:33.740
And there's nothing like
a father to bring you

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:35.390
back down to earth.

00:11:35.390 --> 00:11:38.730
I think I'd been there two days
before he was, turn that

00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:40.626
bloody music down!

00:11:40.626 --> 00:11:43.150
You're not on bloody tour now!

00:11:43.150 --> 00:11:45.360
And I really enjoyed--

00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:47.760
and that was a discovery
for me.

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:50.080
I wouldn't have remembered
that if I

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:51.520
hadn't written a book.

00:11:51.520 --> 00:11:54.150
And that was like, wow.

00:11:54.150 --> 00:11:55.040
ADAM STEWART: That's amazing.

00:11:55.040 --> 00:11:57.690
Why don't we, if you would,
want to take us through a

00:11:57.690 --> 00:11:58.200
passage of the book?

00:11:58.200 --> 00:11:58.880
JOHN TAYLOR: Sure.

00:11:58.880 --> 00:11:59.580
Yeah.

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:02.670
I'm a little bit concerned that
some of the readings are

00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:04.280
a bit long, so bear with me.

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:08.100
I'm going to read a little from
the first chapter, which

00:12:08.100 --> 00:12:10.016
is called Hey Jude.

00:12:10.016 --> 00:12:14.490
I'm four years old, confident
and shy, hair blonder than it

00:12:14.490 --> 00:12:17.780
would be in my teen years, in
shorts and sandals, a young

00:12:17.780 --> 00:12:20.260
prince of the neighborhood.

00:12:20.260 --> 00:12:22.510
The south Birmingham suburb
of Hollywood.

00:12:22.510 --> 00:12:23.700
How perfect.

00:12:23.700 --> 00:12:27.000
10 o'clock in the morning on any
given weekday in 1964, and

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.040
I've stepped down off the porch
[? in wait, ?] kicking

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:31.880
at the grooved concrete
driveway, watching as mom

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:34.830
pulls the front door closed,
locks it up, and puts the key

00:12:34.830 --> 00:12:35.880
in her handbag.

00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:38.430
She puts the handbag in the
shopping bag, and off we go,

00:12:38.430 --> 00:12:41.030
left off the drive and up the
hill that is the street on

00:12:41.030 --> 00:12:42.880
which we live, Simon Road.

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:46.640
Our house is number 34, one up
from where the road ends.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:49.050
We walk together along the
pavement, counting down.

00:12:49.050 --> 00:12:52.500
32, 30, 28.

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:54.600
On the left side of the street
are all the even-numbered,

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:57.910
semi-detached houses, single
buildings designed to function

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:01.500
as two separate homes, houses
twinned with number 36.

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:04.040
Across the street, the odd
numbered houses are detached,

00:13:04.040 --> 00:13:06.600
each building a single dwelling,
all much larger than

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:11.050
ours, and so are the back
gardens, which are long and

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:13.930
tree-filled, and bordered at
the bottom by a stream.

00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:15.880
The driveways are slicker,
too, with space for

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:17.870
more than one car.

00:13:17.870 --> 00:13:20.440
I hold mom's hand, remembering
the Beatles song that is so

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:23.500
often on the radio as the
incline gets steeper.

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:26.570
We reach the crest of the hill
where Simon Road meets Douglas

00:13:26.570 --> 00:13:28.180
Road and turn right.

00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:30.840
We pass a 12 foot high holly
bush, the only evidence I've

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:33.960
found that suggests where
the estate got its name.

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:36.460
We march on, crossing Hollywood
Lane in front of Gay

00:13:36.460 --> 00:13:39.330
Hill Golf Club, an establishment
that will assume

00:13:39.330 --> 00:13:41.970
mythical proportions in my
imagination as a venue for

00:13:41.970 --> 00:13:45.740
wife-swapping parties, not that
anyone in my family ever

00:13:45.740 --> 00:13:47.950
set foot in the place,
and there was no

00:13:47.950 --> 00:13:49.780
truth in the rumor.

00:13:49.780 --> 00:13:53.270
Cars flash by at 20 or even
30 miles an hour.

00:13:53.270 --> 00:13:55.910
We make it to Highter's Heath
Lane, another main artery of

00:13:55.910 --> 00:13:58.000
the neighborhood, which must
be taken if you're visiting

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.170
the old Birmingham of nans and
aunts and uncles, recreational

00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:03.820
parks and bowling greens.

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:06.750
It gets traversed a lot by the
Taylor family at weekends.

00:14:06.750 --> 00:14:09.930
It must also be used by mother
and son if we are to reach our

00:14:09.930 --> 00:14:14.070
destination today, Saint
Jude's Parish Church.

00:14:14.070 --> 00:14:16.750
I would go to many beautiful,
awe- inspiring churches when I

00:14:16.750 --> 00:14:17.400
was older--

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:20.570
St. Patrick's on Fifth Avenue,
St. Peter's in Rome, Notre

00:14:20.570 --> 00:14:24.070
Dame de Paris, but St. Jude's on
Glenavon Road was the most

00:14:24.070 --> 00:14:27.260
pragmatic people's church
anywhere in the First World.

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:30.340
Built in the post World War II
years, St. Jude's was intended

00:14:30.340 --> 00:14:32.460
as a temporary structure,
not meant to last

00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:33.770
more than a few years.

00:14:33.770 --> 00:14:36.620
It's coming up on 20 now, and
yawning with cold air and

00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:40.210
aching joints, single story with
windows every six feet

00:14:40.210 --> 00:14:43.710
along its length, and a roof
of corrugated iron.

00:14:43.710 --> 00:14:47.430
Its crude purity enhanced the
idea the St. Jude's faithful

00:14:47.430 --> 00:14:49.790
had about being the
chosen ones.

00:14:49.790 --> 00:14:52.320
Why else would we gather
together in this cold, ugly

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:55.380
place, unless it was an absolute
certainty that we

00:14:55.380 --> 00:14:57.490
would benefit from it?

00:14:57.490 --> 00:14:59.840
A communal sense of readiness
sends us through the small

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:03.110
lobby, where on raw wooden
tables, literature is offered,

00:15:03.110 --> 00:15:04.960
some for sale, some for free--

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:08.110
textbooks, Bibles, songbooks,
and other merchandise,

00:15:08.110 --> 00:15:11.010
including rosaries, crucifixes,
and pendants of

00:15:11.010 --> 00:15:14.870
St. Jude's, the patron saint
of hopeless cases.

00:15:14.870 --> 00:15:17.370
On into the nave, where there
is a smell of sweat and

00:15:17.370 --> 00:15:18.890
yesterday's incense.

00:15:18.890 --> 00:15:21.720
It's usually cool in here,
sometimes warm, but never hot.

00:15:21.720 --> 00:15:25.420
A tall, red-headed man plays a
rickety looking organ, quietly

00:15:25.420 --> 00:15:27.820
piping sweet music that
is barely there.

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:28.240
[INAUDIBLE]

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:29.930
would call it ambient.

00:15:29.930 --> 00:15:33.100
Candles burn lazily
with a holy scent.

00:15:33.100 --> 00:15:35.110
On the strike of 11:00,
the service begins.

00:15:35.110 --> 00:15:37.970
The priest enters smartly,
followed by a pair of young

00:15:37.970 --> 00:15:41.740
men in white robes, the priest's
team, his posse, one

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:43.930
of whom swings a silver chalice
from which more

00:15:43.930 --> 00:15:45.410
incense issues.

00:15:45.410 --> 00:15:47.930
The air in the church needs a
good cleansing before the good

00:15:47.930 --> 00:15:49.650
father can breathe it.

00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:52.570
He wears elaborate clothing, a
robe of green and gold silk

00:15:52.570 --> 00:15:54.130
with a red cross on his back.

00:15:54.130 --> 00:15:56.620
Beneath the cloak, ankle length
turned up trousers

00:15:56.620 --> 00:15:59.230
reveal the black socks and
black robes of any other

00:15:59.230 --> 00:16:00.910
working man.

00:16:00.910 --> 00:16:03.390
The music surges in volume,
and we all stand.

00:16:03.390 --> 00:16:06.180
The red haired man leads us in
a song we know well, The Lord

00:16:06.180 --> 00:16:07.160
is My Shepherd.

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:09.450
I open the hymnal to
read the words.

00:16:09.450 --> 00:16:11.660
I like this one, but
like Mom, I'm too

00:16:11.660 --> 00:16:13.360
embarrassed to sing out loud.

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:14.280
I wish I could.

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:15.330
I just don't.

00:16:15.330 --> 00:16:17.750
But I like the feeling of
togetherness that comes from

00:16:17.750 --> 00:16:20.750
everyone in the room singing
the same words.

00:16:20.750 --> 00:16:23.040
Once the song is over, the
priest walks to the dais.

00:16:23.040 --> 00:16:26.010
He glances down at his Bible,
opens his hands wide, and

00:16:26.010 --> 00:16:27.420
says, let us pray.

00:16:30.020 --> 00:16:32.650
ADAM STEWART: John, you met
Nick, if the chronology I have

00:16:32.650 --> 00:16:36.010
is correct, in 1971, so seven
or so years after

00:16:36.010 --> 00:16:39.420
this picture is taken.

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:41.850
Music is changing at that time,
and as you guys are

00:16:41.850 --> 00:16:46.400
growing up, Bowie, Roxy Music,
and that kind of glam stuff

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:47.530
starts happening.

00:16:47.530 --> 00:16:50.340
At '76, there's this turn, it's
the Sex Pistols, so you

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:52.320
get this kind of real
change in music.

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:54.690
'78, Duran Duran comes about.

00:16:54.690 --> 00:16:58.150
And you and Nick clearly
have some aspirations.

00:16:58.150 --> 00:17:01.130
Some pretty ambitious goals.

00:17:01.130 --> 00:17:04.020
At what point in the journey
were you like, we've arrived.

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:05.069
This is it.

00:17:05.069 --> 00:17:08.859
This is what we've always
set out to do?

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:12.339
JOHN TAYLOR: Well,
we were lucky.

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:16.750
We connected with a nightclub
in our home city of

00:17:16.750 --> 00:17:19.369
Birmingham, and the guys that
ran the club-- that owned it,

00:17:19.369 --> 00:17:21.530
actually-- were two brothers.

00:17:21.530 --> 00:17:25.579
And it's all about team
building, isn't it, at the end

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:26.540
of the day?

00:17:26.540 --> 00:17:27.420
It just is.

00:17:27.420 --> 00:17:28.890
I don't believe in solo acts.

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:30.840
It's all about building
a team.

00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:35.210
And Nick and I, we were
the founders.

00:17:35.210 --> 00:17:40.730
And then we formed Duran, and
we had a couple of guys come

00:17:40.730 --> 00:17:44.040
in, and then they left.

00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:46.720
Something that I talk about in
the book, how galvanizing it

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:49.700
is when people leave, and they
go on to something else, and

00:17:49.700 --> 00:17:50.950
you go, you fuckers!

00:17:53.120 --> 00:17:54.730
We're going to show them.

00:17:54.730 --> 00:17:56.940
We were written off quite a
few times before we had a

00:17:56.940 --> 00:17:59.530
record deal.

00:17:59.530 --> 00:18:02.670
And then somebody introduced
us to Roger Taylor, who was

00:18:02.670 --> 00:18:06.320
the drummer, and that was when
I started playing bass.

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:08.450
And then it took
us a long time.

00:18:08.450 --> 00:18:12.010
I mean, the funny thing about
Duran Duran is, like, I

00:18:12.010 --> 00:18:14.815
remember Boy George, he
was a Brummie too.

00:18:14.815 --> 00:18:16.990
He spent a lot of time
in Birmingham.

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:22.020
And I remember talking to him at
a wine bar in 1979, and him

00:18:22.020 --> 00:18:23.600
saying to me, what's the
name of your band?

00:18:23.600 --> 00:18:24.830
And we say, Duran Duran.

00:18:24.830 --> 00:18:25.690
He goes, Duran Duran?

00:18:25.690 --> 00:18:27.347
Are they still going?

00:18:27.347 --> 00:18:32.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:34.960
We bounced around our
town for a while.

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:36.130
We went through different--

00:18:36.130 --> 00:18:37.080
finding different--

00:18:37.080 --> 00:18:38.280
then you'd find the right--

00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:39.690
and then the guitar player--

00:18:39.690 --> 00:18:40.920
and then the guitar player
would leave.

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:45.200
But we made the acquaintance
of these two brothers who

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:47.960
became our patrons, and they
started putting a little bit

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:51.670
of money into us, and they gave
us a place to rehearse.

00:18:51.670 --> 00:18:53.470
And the group identity
kind of formed

00:18:53.470 --> 00:18:56.900
itself in this nightclub.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:19:02.470
And then Andy came down
from Newcastle.

00:19:02.470 --> 00:19:05.945
He answered an ad in one of the
national music papers, and

00:19:05.945 --> 00:19:07.650
he came down.

00:19:07.650 --> 00:19:11.940
He was cut from a different
cloth than we were.

00:19:11.940 --> 00:19:13.190
He was hardcore.

00:19:13.190 --> 00:19:16.450
And he knew his music,
you know?

00:19:16.450 --> 00:19:19.690
And then within about six weeks
of him coming-- and I

00:19:19.690 --> 00:19:20.850
mean, he came down.

00:19:20.850 --> 00:19:25.030
He moved from Newcastle 300
miles to Birmingham, and we

00:19:25.030 --> 00:19:26.890
didn't even have a singer.

00:19:26.890 --> 00:19:32.100
That's how confident the three
of us and the managers were,

00:19:32.100 --> 00:19:35.090
that by the time Simon came on
board, we were like, great,

00:19:35.090 --> 00:19:35.930
OK, sign here.

00:19:35.930 --> 00:19:37.855
We're off.

00:19:37.855 --> 00:19:40.140
And the day that Simon came
in, he walked up to the

00:19:40.140 --> 00:19:40.690
microphone.

00:19:40.690 --> 00:19:41.670
We were playing.

00:19:41.670 --> 00:19:43.175
We'd already been working
on the architecture

00:19:43.175 --> 00:19:44.150
of the sound, right?

00:19:44.150 --> 00:19:46.710
So we knew what the band's sound
was going to be like,

00:19:46.710 --> 00:19:48.400
but we needed a voice.

00:19:48.400 --> 00:19:52.930
Simon came in, he got a blue
exercise book that he used to

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:56.530
make notes, like ideas for
poems and whatnot.

00:19:56.530 --> 00:19:58.100
I love "Nashville,"
by the way.

00:19:58.100 --> 00:19:59.400
I just want to put
that out there.

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:02.380
I think "Nashville" is the best
new show, and I love the

00:20:02.380 --> 00:20:06.120
way they address songwriting
and collaboration.

00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:07.270
It's smart.

00:20:07.270 --> 00:20:08.580
It's really well done.

00:20:08.580 --> 00:20:12.270
And Simon had a book with some
words in it, and guys like

00:20:12.270 --> 00:20:14.710
that in the music business
are priceless.

00:20:14.710 --> 00:20:15.990
There are so few of them.

00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:18.680
It's so easy to make a beat, but
somebody comes in with a

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:22.070
decent bit of poetry on
paper, sign them.

00:20:22.070 --> 00:20:24.200
Simon walked over to
the microphone and

00:20:24.200 --> 00:20:26.110
just, well, try this.

00:20:26.110 --> 00:20:27.100
Blah blah blah.

00:20:27.100 --> 00:20:28.140
And then that was it.

00:20:28.140 --> 00:20:29.250
We were off.

00:20:29.250 --> 00:20:29.980
And we said, right.

00:20:29.980 --> 00:20:31.360
We've got a gig in four weeks.

00:20:34.460 --> 00:20:36.091
Let's write some songs.

00:20:36.091 --> 00:20:39.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:42.170
ADAM STEWART: I mean, Duran
Duran certainly cut a path

00:20:42.170 --> 00:20:44.530
that was different than really,
just about anyone else

00:20:44.530 --> 00:20:46.930
at that time, because you
brought together different

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:49.200
factors and things that were
happening in music.

00:20:49.200 --> 00:20:50.970
But I'm curious,
because disco.

00:20:50.970 --> 00:20:52.980
And you talk a little bit about
Chic in the book and

00:20:52.980 --> 00:20:55.800
everything like that, because
there's an aspect of new wave,

00:20:55.800 --> 00:20:58.240
and an aspect of disco, and
especially in the early Duran

00:20:58.240 --> 00:20:59.540
Duran music.

00:20:59.540 --> 00:21:01.670
Can you talk a little bit about
how your sound came

00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:03.250
together as a band?

00:21:03.250 --> 00:21:07.520
JOHN TAYLOR: Well, I remember
being in a pub one lunchtime

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:08.090
in Birmingham.

00:21:08.090 --> 00:21:11.530
I went to art college
for a year, and I

00:21:11.530 --> 00:21:13.300
was on my lunch break.

00:21:13.300 --> 00:21:17.950
And I remember the jukebox in
the pub, and "Anarchy In the

00:21:17.950 --> 00:21:18.750
UK" came on.

00:21:18.750 --> 00:21:19.340
Sex Pistols.

00:21:19.340 --> 00:21:23.360
That was an anthem for me--

00:21:23.360 --> 00:21:24.750
really massive record.

00:21:24.750 --> 00:21:27.160
And then Chic came
on after that.

00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:29.460
"Everybody Dance,"
I think it was.

00:21:29.460 --> 00:21:31.840
And I remember sitting
there thinking, I

00:21:31.840 --> 00:21:32.610
love both these songs.

00:21:32.610 --> 00:21:36.000
It was like being Republican and
Democrat at the same time.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:37.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:37.190 --> 00:21:40.380
JOHN TAYLOR: It's like
it was either or.

00:21:40.380 --> 00:21:41.270
You can't be both.

00:21:41.270 --> 00:21:43.240
And I thought, but I am both.

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:45.970
I love both of those musics.

00:21:45.970 --> 00:21:49.110
And I thought, god, if we could
just somehow combine

00:21:49.110 --> 00:21:51.190
those two things.

00:21:51.190 --> 00:21:54.460
And the key for me was to become
a bass player, because

00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:58.130
the thing about Chic's music
and disco music that really

00:21:58.130 --> 00:22:00.390
caught my attention
was the bass.

00:22:00.390 --> 00:22:02.320
And the music that I've been
listening to-- the bands that

00:22:02.320 --> 00:22:06.280
I've been following in my late
teens were bands like The

00:22:06.280 --> 00:22:08.860
Clash that were really
guitar-driven.

00:22:08.860 --> 00:22:12.050
The bass players just followed
the changes.

00:22:12.050 --> 00:22:14.390
Nobody really listened
to the bass.

00:22:14.390 --> 00:22:16.840
It was just part of the sound.

00:22:16.840 --> 00:22:19.870
But in disco, the bass almost
felt like it was the lead

00:22:19.870 --> 00:22:20.300
instrument.

00:22:20.300 --> 00:22:23.980
And so I started playing with
Rog, and fortunately, Roger

00:22:23.980 --> 00:22:25.020
was also a punk.

00:22:25.020 --> 00:22:27.090
But he was kind of like, yeah.

00:22:27.090 --> 00:22:29.500
Like "Another One Bites
the Dust," you know?

00:22:29.500 --> 00:22:30.750
[HUMMING "ANOTHER ONE
BITES THE DUST"]

00:22:33.870 --> 00:22:36.510
You're doing it together,
and it's so much fun.

00:22:36.510 --> 00:22:39.420
And then you bring in the big
guitars over the top of that,

00:22:39.420 --> 00:22:40.910
and then maybe you've
got something.

00:22:40.910 --> 00:22:42.360
And that's kind of like
what we were.

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:46.910
And then at the same time, these
were the days of the

00:22:46.910 --> 00:22:49.750
first affordable synthesizers.

00:22:49.750 --> 00:22:53.235
I think we got one of the first
Wasp synthesizers which

00:22:53.235 --> 00:22:54.060
came into Birmingham.

00:22:54.060 --> 00:22:55.430
It was about this big,
it was plastic.

00:22:55.430 --> 00:22:58.010
It cost 199 pounds.

00:22:58.010 --> 00:22:59.210
And you had to hold it down.

00:22:59.210 --> 00:23:04.700
[IMITATING SYNTHESIZER SOUNDS]

00:23:04.700 --> 00:23:06.850
And you put a beat to that,
and you've got techno.

00:23:06.850 --> 00:23:08.100
ADAM STEWART: Cool.

00:23:10.790 --> 00:23:13.360
In the book, you talk a lot
about celebrity, and your

00:23:13.360 --> 00:23:16.490
celebrity, and what
you went through.

00:23:16.490 --> 00:23:17.440
Talk to us a little bit.

00:23:17.440 --> 00:23:20.150
What was the best and the
worst part of celebrity?

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:26.440
JOHN TAYLOR: I think
the best part--

00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:30.530
I'm reaping the rewards of it
now, really, because there are

00:23:30.530 --> 00:23:33.520
just so many people out
there that care.

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:35.610
When you've been a part of--

00:23:35.610 --> 00:23:39.950
I mean, I know how much
Bowie means to me.

00:23:39.950 --> 00:23:43.890
There's a handful of guys that
helped me become, that helped

00:23:43.890 --> 00:23:46.150
me through that really
difficult time

00:23:46.150 --> 00:23:48.460
from 13 to 15, 16.

00:23:48.460 --> 00:23:53.800
And I love him like I love
my dad or my wife.

00:23:53.800 --> 00:23:57.440
And we had the privilege to
be a part of that for a

00:23:57.440 --> 00:24:00.710
generation of teens.

00:24:00.710 --> 00:24:02.520
So there are a lot of
people out there

00:24:02.520 --> 00:24:04.130
that we're very important.

00:24:04.130 --> 00:24:06.380
We play an important part
in their lives.

00:24:06.380 --> 00:24:08.540
And it's very useful when you
want to get a table in a

00:24:08.540 --> 00:24:09.790
