hear that at the time, where

00:35:10.700 --> 00:35:12.840
everything is kind of going
crazy in your life in New

00:35:12.840 --> 00:35:16.190
York, you're still thinking
about back home.

00:35:16.190 --> 00:35:18.320
And I think that was one of
those things, again, that I

00:35:18.320 --> 00:35:19.970
just feel connected with a
lot of different people.

00:35:22.500 --> 00:35:25.580
30 years now, plus, I think,
into Duran Duran.

00:35:25.580 --> 00:35:26.590
What's it like for you today?

00:35:26.590 --> 00:35:27.150
JOHN TAYLOR: It's good.

00:35:27.150 --> 00:35:27.700
It's good.

00:35:27.700 --> 00:35:31.700
I'm glad I got to write the
book over the last year,

00:35:31.700 --> 00:35:33.650
because we've had a
really good time.

00:35:33.650 --> 00:35:37.850
I mean, we did our
last album as a

00:35:37.850 --> 00:35:39.880
digital download on iTunes.

00:35:39.880 --> 00:35:44.730
It felt like we finally got
right with new media.

00:35:44.730 --> 00:35:46.910
For a couple of years, we
just couldn't relate.

00:35:46.910 --> 00:35:49.980
We couldn't find our place
in the industry.

00:35:49.980 --> 00:35:51.690
And this last album,
we were lucky.

00:35:51.690 --> 00:35:53.850
Mark Ronson stepped in
and produced, and

00:35:53.850 --> 00:35:55.310
he gave us a sense--

00:35:55.310 --> 00:35:57.640
just having in the room,
you feel hipper.

00:35:57.640 --> 00:35:59.730
I mean, that was a good thing.

00:35:59.730 --> 00:36:04.360
And then we started getting into
social media, networking,

00:36:04.360 --> 00:36:13.170
promoting the album, and finding
what that did for the

00:36:13.170 --> 00:36:16.520
connectivity of our fans
was just amazing.

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:17.340
And I felt it.

00:36:17.340 --> 00:36:28.790
I mean, the album came out just
before Christmas of 2010,

00:36:28.790 --> 00:36:32.280
at the end of not last year,
the year before.

00:36:32.280 --> 00:36:35.500
And we started getting into
social networking.

00:36:35.500 --> 00:36:38.480
And the first show that we did
was in London about three

00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:39.480
months later.

00:36:39.480 --> 00:36:43.080
And the feeling in the room
was so charged up.

00:36:43.080 --> 00:36:46.240
It was completely different to
anything that we'd done in the

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:47.710
previous five years.

00:36:47.710 --> 00:36:49.600
And I put that down to
social networking.

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:51.610
And people were showing up, and
they were going, hey, how

00:36:51.610 --> 00:36:52.480
are you doing?

00:36:52.480 --> 00:36:55.540
And they'd connected, because
when the band goes on social

00:36:55.540 --> 00:36:57.670
networking, people start signing
on, following us on

00:36:57.670 --> 00:36:59.690
Twitter, getting onto Facebook,
and they start

00:36:59.690 --> 00:37:00.220
connecting.

00:37:00.220 --> 00:37:04.410
And suddenly, it's like
Duran fans reunited.

00:37:04.410 --> 00:37:08.010
It's like one of those
friend networks.

00:37:08.010 --> 00:37:12.690
And it's generated a lot of
energy around the band.

00:37:12.690 --> 00:37:15.720
And I don't even worry about
getting in the charts anymore.

00:37:15.720 --> 00:37:16.790
It's not about that.

00:37:16.790 --> 00:37:19.320
It's just, like, we've got
this really strong family

00:37:19.320 --> 00:37:22.830
that's kind of re-committed
itself to each other, and

00:37:22.830 --> 00:37:26.150
actually is kind of
growing again.

00:37:26.150 --> 00:37:28.320
So it's been an interesting
couple of years.

00:37:28.320 --> 00:37:31.550
And we're going to get back and
do another album with Mark

00:37:31.550 --> 00:37:33.350
in the spring.

00:37:33.350 --> 00:37:34.797
And we're really enjoying
our music.

00:37:34.797 --> 00:37:36.140
ADAM STEWART: Terriffic.

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:38.504
Any questions?

00:37:38.504 --> 00:37:40.300
AUDIENCE: Who are your current
musical inspirations?

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:46.385
JOHN TAYLOR: I was playing
Led Zeppelin yesterday.

00:37:49.110 --> 00:37:52.005
They're never not going
to be relevant.

00:37:52.005 --> 00:37:55.600
I've been listening to a lot of
folk rock lately, actually.

00:37:55.600 --> 00:37:57.530
Bert Jansch, John Renbourn.

00:37:57.530 --> 00:38:01.730
Sort of old English
guitar music.

00:38:01.730 --> 00:38:03.790
But I like modern music.

00:38:03.790 --> 00:38:08.310
I like to hear great
modern music.

00:38:08.310 --> 00:38:09.270
[INAUDIBLE]

00:38:09.270 --> 00:38:13.600
is a DJ that I really like,
and he's put an album out.

00:38:13.600 --> 00:38:17.430
It's like a curated DJ set
that's kind of like my album

00:38:17.430 --> 00:38:20.120
of choice at the moment.

00:38:20.120 --> 00:38:21.880
You just have to look.

00:38:21.880 --> 00:38:26.880
Like last year, I was on the
road in England, and I was

00:38:26.880 --> 00:38:28.255
listening to Louis Armstrong.

00:38:28.255 --> 00:38:29.870
I thought, this is what
it's come to.

00:38:29.870 --> 00:38:31.060
I'm listening to music
from the '30s.

00:38:31.060 --> 00:38:34.470
That's how crap contemporary
music is.

00:38:34.470 --> 00:38:37.890
And I just chanced upon this
record store called Piccadilly

00:38:37.890 --> 00:38:39.530
Records in Manchester.

00:38:39.530 --> 00:38:45.730
I went in-- it was December, and
they'd curated the year's

00:38:45.730 --> 00:38:47.940
best music, and they printed
up a pamphlet.

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:50.470
You know, Amoeba do it, Rough
Trade do it in London.

00:38:50.470 --> 00:38:53.590
And they printed up a pamphlet,
and all the staff

00:38:53.590 --> 00:38:56.940
from the record store got to
write a little blurb about

00:38:56.940 --> 00:38:58.820
what they thought was
the important best

00:38:58.820 --> 00:38:59.920
music of the year.

00:38:59.920 --> 00:39:02.710
And I'm opening up this
pamphlet, and almost every one

00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:06.090
of them is saying, wow, the
best music of 2011--

00:39:06.090 --> 00:39:07.030
I don't know where to begin.

00:39:07.030 --> 00:39:09.520
It was such a fantastic
year for music.

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:12.860
And I'm thinking, fantastic
year for music?

00:39:12.860 --> 00:39:17.120
And I realized how out
of touch I was.

00:39:17.120 --> 00:39:21.340
And I bought half
a dozen albums.

00:39:21.340 --> 00:39:24.145
Their top six albums
of the year.

00:39:24.145 --> 00:39:24.900
Every one of them--

00:39:24.900 --> 00:39:29.550
Kurt Vile, Washed
Out, Metronomy.

00:39:29.550 --> 00:39:33.122
I mean, half a dozen bands that
I'd not heard of became

00:39:33.122 --> 00:39:35.190
my new favorite bands.

00:39:35.190 --> 00:39:37.000
So I just have to
get out there.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:38.987
If I want to be into
contemporary music, I just

00:39:38.987 --> 00:39:40.448
have to make an effort.

00:39:40.448 --> 00:39:42.370
Thanks.

00:39:42.370 --> 00:39:44.490
AUDIENCE: I sort of have a
follow-up question to that,

00:39:44.490 --> 00:39:46.230
for music discovery.

00:39:46.230 --> 00:39:50.710
For your own music that you
listen to, do you find

00:39:50.710 --> 00:39:55.200
yourself using digital services,
like you said, going

00:39:55.200 --> 00:39:55.990
to record stores?

00:39:55.990 --> 00:39:59.000
And if you are using digital
services, are you using

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:02.320
Spotify, or YouTube,
or iTunes?

00:40:02.320 --> 00:40:02.810
JOHN TAYLOR: Yeah.

00:40:02.810 --> 00:40:11.570
I mean, I'm on the hunt all the
time for music that I have

00:40:11.570 --> 00:40:13.170
not heard before.

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:14.300
It doesn't have to be new.

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:15.000
It can be old.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.260
But something that's going
to inspire me--

00:40:17.260 --> 00:40:18.900
that's going to keep
me interested.

00:40:18.900 --> 00:40:23.150
I find that as a bass player,
I can only listen to

00:40:23.150 --> 00:40:26.240
contemporary music for so long,
because most of the

00:40:26.240 --> 00:40:30.610
great bass work is older.

00:40:30.610 --> 00:40:32.460
But I've always got a stack
of stuff that I'm

00:40:32.460 --> 00:40:34.320
working my way through.

00:40:34.320 --> 00:40:39.470
I do use iTunes if there's
something that I need now.

00:40:39.470 --> 00:40:42.830
But if it's something that's
important to me, I'm still

00:40:42.830 --> 00:40:44.350
attached to the physical
product.

00:40:44.350 --> 00:40:47.370
I've sort of gotten back into
vintage vinyl the way some

00:40:47.370 --> 00:40:49.366
people get into vintage wines.

00:40:49.366 --> 00:40:53.920
I mean, the idea of taking
"Exile on Main St." out maybe

00:40:53.920 --> 00:40:58.440
once every two years,
and putting it on--

00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:01.570
that's like uncorking a vintage
bottle of wine.

00:41:01.570 --> 00:41:03.880
I just want to do it, and then
I don't want to hear it for

00:41:03.880 --> 00:41:06.530
another two years.

00:41:06.530 --> 00:41:10.670
Because music, like any art,
it doesn't have infinite

00:41:10.670 --> 00:41:12.890
amounts of energy in it.

00:41:12.890 --> 00:41:14.030
You have to pace yourself
in your

00:41:14.030 --> 00:41:17.540
appreciation of it, I find.

00:41:17.540 --> 00:41:21.560
I also found-- we were talking
over lunch how the music, like

00:41:21.560 --> 00:41:25.600
those three bands that I just
mentioned, I still am attached

00:41:25.600 --> 00:41:26.900
to imagery.

00:41:26.900 --> 00:41:32.740
Like, I still like packaging
that gives me something more,

00:41:32.740 --> 00:41:35.020
something visual that I can
connect with the music that

00:41:35.020 --> 00:41:36.530
I'm listening to.

00:41:36.530 --> 00:41:39.150
And I find that if it's music
that I'm going around telling

00:41:39.150 --> 00:41:40.840
everybody, you've got
to get this band!

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:42.170
You've got to buy this!

00:41:42.170 --> 00:41:47.140
Then I own that physical
product.

00:41:47.140 --> 00:41:47.830
I've got to have it.

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:49.187
I've got to have something
that I can

00:41:49.187 --> 00:41:50.290
relate to on that level.

00:41:50.290 --> 00:41:54.400
I haven't been able to
let go of that yet.

00:41:54.400 --> 00:41:54.773
Thanks.

00:41:54.773 --> 00:41:56.023
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:41:59.450 --> 00:42:01.730
AUDIENCE: Can you fill us in on
how you guys came up with

00:42:01.730 --> 00:42:03.085
the name Duran Duran?

00:42:03.085 --> 00:42:03.350
JOHN TAYLOR: Yeah.

00:42:03.350 --> 00:42:11.590
It's from the film "Barbarella"
with Jane Fonda

00:42:11.590 --> 00:42:14.600
as the sexy lady astronaut.

00:42:17.530 --> 00:42:21.940
It was taken from a French
cartoon strip, and

00:42:21.940 --> 00:42:22.900
the film is a really--

00:42:22.900 --> 00:42:24.680
Roger Vadim.

00:42:24.680 --> 00:42:28.630
It's a really extraordinary
film.

00:42:28.630 --> 00:42:31.620
It's beautifully shot,
kind of kitsch.

00:42:31.620 --> 00:42:36.670
And I think the opening line in
the film is Barbarella, you

00:42:36.670 --> 00:42:40.700
must find Duran Duran from
the planet Earth.

00:42:40.700 --> 00:42:42.170
That's the opening
line in the film.

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:46.160
And Duran Duran is this
criminal, this sort of

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:51.470
trans-universal criminal who has
stolen some machine that

00:42:51.470 --> 00:42:53.505
is guaranteed to give
women pleasure.

00:42:53.505 --> 00:42:56.040
But that had nothing to do
with that choice of name.

00:42:56.040 --> 00:42:57.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:57.880 --> 00:43:00.440
I mean, it was just a time
when everybody was naming

00:43:00.440 --> 00:43:02.260
their band The something.

00:43:02.260 --> 00:43:05.150
The Damned, The Boys,
The Clash.

00:43:05.150 --> 00:43:07.370
So I liked the idea
that this had

00:43:07.370 --> 00:43:10.530
something that seemed modern.

00:43:10.530 --> 00:43:13.730
AUDIENCE: Do you have a favorite
Duran Duran album or

00:43:13.730 --> 00:43:15.100
single or video?

00:43:15.100 --> 00:43:18.730
JOHN TAYLOR: Well, I think "Rio"
is probably the album

00:43:18.730 --> 00:43:21.570
that's just where we really
caught the wave.

00:43:21.570 --> 00:43:25.390
And I think every note
of it works.

00:43:25.390 --> 00:43:26.100
Better than works.

00:43:26.100 --> 00:43:29.610
Every note of it is great.

00:43:29.610 --> 00:43:31.040
But I'm proud of a lot.

00:43:31.040 --> 00:43:33.360
I'm proud of "Ordinary World"
as a song very much.

00:43:37.110 --> 00:43:38.110
"Notorious."

00:43:38.110 --> 00:43:40.860
"View To A Kill." You know,
that's interesting.

00:43:40.860 --> 00:43:43.460
Writing a Bond theme is like
designing a Rolls Royce.

00:43:43.460 --> 00:43:47.380
It's really, really difficult,
because you've got so many

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:50.980
boxes you have to tick for
it to work for the Bond

00:43:50.980 --> 00:43:53.930
franchise, but I think we did
a really good job with that.

00:43:53.930 --> 00:43:55.310
And that was a difficult
song to write.

00:43:55.310 --> 00:43:58.310
There was a lot of infighting
going on while we were doing

00:43:58.310 --> 00:43:59.380
it, but I'm really happy
with that one.

00:43:59.380 --> 00:44:01.350
AUDIENCE: That was a
cool video, too.

00:44:01.350 --> 00:44:01.760
JOHN TAYLOR: You think so?

00:44:01.760 --> 00:44:03.188
See, I hate that video.

00:44:03.188 --> 00:44:05.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:05.100 --> 00:44:06.060
AUDIENCE: Wow.

00:44:06.060 --> 00:44:08.950
JOHN TAYLOR: It's not
one of my favorites.

00:44:08.950 --> 00:44:10.550
I'd rather watch the
titles from the

00:44:10.550 --> 00:44:13.300
film unfurl, you know?

00:44:13.300 --> 00:44:13.740
Thanks.

00:44:13.740 --> 00:44:15.450
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:15.450 --> 00:44:16.460
ADAM STEWART: Any
other questions?

00:44:16.460 --> 00:44:17.130
Great.

00:44:17.130 --> 00:44:19.600
Terrific.

00:44:19.600 --> 00:44:21.280
AUDIENCE: Have you tried playing
your song on "Rock

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:21.860
Band?"

00:44:21.860 --> 00:44:22.794
JOHN TAYLOR: No!

00:44:22.794 --> 00:44:23.728
No!

00:44:23.728 --> 00:44:24.662
Never.

00:44:24.662 --> 00:44:26.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:26.530 --> 00:44:27.330
AUDIENCE: And do you get--

00:44:27.330 --> 00:44:29.400
because they change
the level, right.

00:44:29.400 --> 00:44:30.970
Some songs are harder
than others.

00:44:30.970 --> 00:44:32.790
Do you appreciate it if
your song is the easy

00:44:32.790 --> 00:44:34.370
song or the hard song?

00:44:34.370 --> 00:44:34.890
JOHN TAYLOR: No.

00:44:34.890 --> 00:44:37.240
You could be talking to me
about brain surgery.

00:44:37.240 --> 00:44:41.520
I know nothing about
"Rock Band."

00:44:41.520 --> 00:44:43.180
AUDIENCE: I'm wondering if you
can kind of paint a picture

00:44:43.180 --> 00:44:48.080
for us of what it was like, the
first public performance

00:44:48.080 --> 00:44:52.710
that you did as the Fab Five
lineup with Simon.

00:44:52.710 --> 00:44:54.380
What was that night like?

00:44:54.380 --> 00:44:56.360
Was it a disaster,
or was it magic--

00:44:56.360 --> 00:44:59.770
everything came together?

00:44:59.770 --> 00:45:02.150
JOHN TAYLOR: Well, again, we've
got to go back to the

00:45:02.150 --> 00:45:04.850
club that we were based out of,
which was a club called

00:45:04.850 --> 00:45:07.240
the Rum Runner in Birmingham.

00:45:07.240 --> 00:45:09.860
And it was a very culty
kind of scene.

00:45:09.860 --> 00:45:13.500
It was a very fashion-oriented
scene.

00:45:13.500 --> 00:45:18.300
It was kind of post punk, and
it was this kind of glamor

00:45:18.300 --> 00:45:20.590
that was coming back.

00:45:20.590 --> 00:45:26.750
It was very ambiguous,
sexually.

00:45:26.750 --> 00:45:29.440
There was a lot of gays
on the scene.

00:45:29.440 --> 00:45:30.720
People were just into
dressing up.

00:45:30.720 --> 00:45:32.970
Everybody did something
with their hair--

00:45:32.970 --> 00:45:35.040
dyed, coiffed, whatever.

00:45:35.040 --> 00:45:38.120
And it was like a kind
of oasis, really.

00:45:38.120 --> 00:45:39.940
A post-punk oasis.

00:45:39.940 --> 00:45:42.470
And the kind of music that was
popular there was this sort of

00:45:42.470 --> 00:45:45.530
new electronic vibe,
like Simple Minds,

00:45:45.530 --> 00:45:47.300
Japan, bands like that.

00:45:47.300 --> 00:45:50.050
And so we became the
house band there.

00:45:50.050 --> 00:45:52.670
And we were rehearsing there.

00:45:52.670 --> 00:45:55.440
And we all had jobs there.

00:45:55.440 --> 00:45:58.400
We would all work behind the
bar, or work on the door.

00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:01.960
And in return for that, the
owners had given us this--

00:46:01.960 --> 00:46:07.490
we had a rehearsal space
just off the main bar.

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:10.280
And on a Friday night, which was
a really hot night in the

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:13.560
club, we'd go up and turn on our
gear, and we'd invite some

00:46:13.560 --> 00:46:17.190
of our friends up at midnight,
and we'd just play some songs

00:46:17.190 --> 00:46:19.820
while everybody was dancing
down on the floor.

00:46:23.060 --> 00:46:28.430
So when we had the final debut,
as I call it, which was

00:46:28.430 --> 00:46:33.900
like version five of the band,
we were playing to friends.

00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:35.810
And everybody kind of knew us.

00:46:35.810 --> 00:46:39.360
And there was a sense of, like,
OK, these are our guys.

00:46:39.360 --> 00:46:40.610
This is our band.

00:46:44.020 --> 00:46:46.520
It's not like a foot
stomping kind of--

00:46:46.520 --> 00:46:48.120
it's not like, a yeah
kind of scene.

00:46:48.120 --> 00:46:50.740
It was like, hmm, okay,
yeah, cool.

00:46:54.630 --> 00:46:56.100
And yeah.

00:46:56.100 --> 00:46:58.870
I mean, there are one or two
pictures from that particular

00:46:58.870 --> 00:47:00.126
show in the book, in fact.

00:47:00.126 --> 00:47:02.340
I'll point them out
to you afterwards.

00:47:02.340 --> 00:47:03.840
Thanks.

00:47:03.840 --> 00:47:05.410
ADAM STEWART: Any
other questions?

00:47:05.410 --> 00:47:07.780
AUDIENCE: What was going on
the band when Arcadia--

00:47:07.780 --> 00:47:09.550
kind of the branch out there?

00:47:09.550 --> 00:47:10.950
Were you guys broken up, or--

00:47:10.950 --> 00:47:12.050
JOHN TAYLOR: Yeah.

00:47:12.050 --> 00:47:13.710
I mean, I feel, in a way,
we kind of had.

00:47:13.710 --> 00:47:16.350
I mean, it's funny.

00:47:16.350 --> 00:47:21.290
The pressure was so great in the
early, mid '80s, just to

00:47:21.290 --> 00:47:23.120
write big hits.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:24.500
And we kind of--

00:47:27.832 --> 00:47:30.870
we weren't all agreeing
on the direction

00:47:30.870 --> 00:47:33.500
the band should take.

00:47:33.500 --> 00:47:36.520
So when we finished the third
album, Andy and I decided we

00:47:36.520 --> 00:47:39.300
wanted to do a side project.

00:47:39.300 --> 00:47:47.290
And so over time, we connected
with Robert Palmer, Tony

00:47:47.290 --> 00:47:50.750
Thompson, Bernard Edwards, the
rhythm section from Chic, and

00:47:50.750 --> 00:47:53.380
we made that album.

00:47:53.380 --> 00:47:56.460
And then Simon, Nick, and Roger
kind of countered that

00:47:56.460 --> 00:47:59.540
with Arcadia.

00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:02.470
I mean, it was difficult.

00:48:02.470 --> 00:48:04.930
Nine months, maybe, where we
were very much-- there were

00:48:04.930 --> 00:48:08.390
two camps, and that's
in the book.

00:48:08.390 --> 00:48:14.360
Because we were kind of fighting
with the managers,

00:48:14.360 --> 00:48:17.793
and it wasn't a happy
time, really.

00:48:17.793 --> 00:48:19.015
It was quite difficult.

00:48:19.015 --> 00:48:21.470
But it's in there.

00:48:21.470 --> 00:48:23.800
Any more for any more?

00:48:23.800 --> 00:48:25.510
ADAM STEWART: I think that's
a good question to segue,

00:48:25.510 --> 00:48:26.800
actually, into the
last reading.

00:48:26.800 --> 00:48:28.050
JOHN TAYLOR: OK.

00:48:30.030 --> 00:48:34.850
We got to play Coachella last
year, and it was a big one for

00:48:34.850 --> 00:48:35.980
me, because I've got kids.

00:48:35.980 --> 00:48:38.690
I've got teenage kids that
have been telling me for

00:48:38.690 --> 00:48:42.630
years, you guys got to
play Coachella, man.

00:48:42.630 --> 00:48:47.380
It was like final validation
with the teenagers.

00:48:47.380 --> 00:48:48.065
But it was magical.

00:48:48.065 --> 00:48:49.320
It was magical.

00:48:49.320 --> 00:48:54.010
So I chose to end the
book on that night.

00:48:54.010 --> 00:48:56.150
Behind the stage, to the
side of the ramp,

00:48:56.150 --> 00:48:57.960
our band has gathered.

00:48:57.960 --> 00:49:01.050
We stepped off the pair of golf
carts that had brought us

00:49:01.050 --> 00:49:02.930
the half mile from our dressing
room in battery

00:49:02.930 --> 00:49:04.160
powered silence.

00:49:04.160 --> 00:49:06.530
The air is warm and
electric blue.

00:49:06.530 --> 00:49:09.160
We acknowledge each other
without words, using nods and

00:49:09.160 --> 00:49:12.760
smiles, back slaps, and other
gestures of encouragement.

00:49:12.760 --> 00:49:14.180
Instincts surge.

00:49:14.180 --> 00:49:16.500
Every other concern
falls away.

00:49:16.500 --> 00:49:20.890
Since 1981, we've released our
songs on vinyl, cassette tape,

00:49:20.890 --> 00:49:24.530
CD, 8 track, digital audio tape,
mini disc, ringtones,

00:49:24.530 --> 00:49:28.530
MP3, streaming, and download,
for purchase or rental.

00:49:28.530 --> 00:49:31.330
I've long since learned to relax
and cease worrying about

00:49:31.330 --> 00:49:34.160
how the music finds its
way to your ears.

00:49:34.160 --> 00:49:35.240
Just play.

00:49:35.240 --> 00:49:36.610
Just write.

00:49:36.610 --> 00:49:40.230
By the time we begin the "All
You Need Is Now" tour, which

00:49:40.230 --> 00:49:43.000
tonight's performance at
Coachella is a part of,

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:45.900
excitement levels have
reached fever pitch.

00:49:45.900 --> 00:49:48.520
We've come a long way to get to
this holy place, Coachella,

00:49:48.520 --> 00:49:50.960
and a lot has changed in
the last 30 years.

00:49:50.960 --> 00:49:55.800
Cell phones, computers, SUVs,
nose hair trimmers,

00:49:55.800 --> 00:50:00.140
supplements, Propecia, paperless
itineraries, in-room

00:50:00.140 --> 00:50:04.150
humidifiers, steam rooms,
saunas, and gyms, pre-show

00:50:04.150 --> 00:50:07.850
massage, Twitter, Spotify,
and Google.

00:50:07.850 --> 00:50:10.930
Touring with 3,000 songs in my
pocket and 30 books on an

00:50:10.930 --> 00:50:14.680
iPad, therapy by Skype, great
coffee everywhere.

00:50:14.680 --> 00:50:16.550
Another difference is out there,
where there are just as

00:50:16.550 --> 00:50:19.690
many men as women in the
audience tonight.

00:50:19.690 --> 00:50:23.260
At day's end, my job is to be
a catalyst for connectivity,

00:50:23.260 --> 00:50:25.490
to help bring people closer
together, men and

00:50:25.490 --> 00:50:27.040
women, girls and boys.

00:50:27.040 --> 00:50:29.720
That's what the music
has done for me.

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:32.140
What hasn't changed are the
notes that run up and down the

00:50:32.140 --> 00:50:35.040
neck of the bass and the feeling
that hits you when one

00:50:35.040 --> 00:50:38.180
note rubs against another in a
way that sets the hair up on

00:50:38.180 --> 00:50:40.890
the back of your neck, and the
sound of the crowd, and the

00:50:40.890 --> 00:50:43.370
feeling of adrenaline that
charges through my body when I

00:50:43.370 --> 00:50:46.310
hear it holding that
four-stringed machine gun on

00:50:46.310 --> 00:50:49.950
stage less than six feet
away from you.

00:50:49.950 --> 00:50:52.550
Simon is running through his
vocal warmups which we so

00:50:52.550 --> 00:50:54.170
often rib him about.

00:50:54.170 --> 00:50:57.190
Nick has a plastic cup in his
left hand, and is taking sips

00:50:57.190 --> 00:51:00.330
from it, now reaching his right
hand upward to flash a

00:51:00.330 --> 00:51:02.140
snapshot on his camera.

00:51:02.140 --> 00:51:05.300
We all fiddle with our in-ear
monitors, trying the volume,

00:51:05.300 --> 00:51:07.050
listening for interference.

00:51:07.050 --> 00:51:08.820
A photographer from
"Spin Magazine"

00:51:08.820 --> 00:51:10.220
wants to take a picture.

00:51:10.220 --> 00:51:13.050
We assemble reluctantly,
everyone just wanting to get

00:51:13.050 --> 00:51:14.670
on with the show.

00:51:14.670 --> 00:51:17.440
It's an outdoor festival, so
tour manager Craig will not

00:51:17.440 --> 00:51:20.500
get to give his usual cue to
take the house lights down.

00:51:20.500 --> 00:51:22.640
Tonight, that is one of
God's jobs, and what a

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:24.540
job of it he is doing.

00:51:24.540 --> 00:51:26.760
A glittering bauble of sunlight
fights to stay above

00:51:26.760 --> 00:51:27.810
the horizon.

00:51:27.810 --> 00:51:30.640
A full moon appears, a
late-coming VIP that takes a

00:51:30.640 --> 00:51:33.640
seat above the lighting gantry
at 11 o'clock high.

00:51:33.640 --> 00:51:36.140
Nature presents for us a better
light show than any

00:51:36.140 --> 00:51:38.590
human could ever have created.

00:51:38.590 --> 00:51:40.050
We walk together up the ramp.

00:51:40.050 --> 00:51:42.600
The stage is set, the
electronics are primed, the

00:51:42.600 --> 00:51:43.820
audience ready.

00:51:43.820 --> 00:51:46.930
Nick walks on first in
a black net snood

00:51:46.930 --> 00:51:48.315
borrowed from Lady Gaga.

00:51:48.315 --> 00:51:50.191
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:50.191 --> 00:51:52.960
JOHN TAYLOR: He walks across the
stage and onto his riser,

00:51:52.960 --> 00:51:55.540
puts down his camera, and
touches the Andromeda

00:51:55.540 --> 00:51:58.600
synthesizer from which issues
forth a sample of the exact

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:01.940
sound he used to begin our first
single, "Planet Earth,"

00:52:01.940 --> 00:52:05.070
written and recorded
over 30 years ago.

00:52:05.070 --> 00:52:06.530
My heart is pounding.

00:52:06.530 --> 00:52:09.360
There is no better time than
this, and I'm about to take

00:52:09.360 --> 00:52:11.580
the stage, and the future
belongs to me.

00:52:11.580 --> 00:52:14.390
This is what the moment feels
like as I walk out onto the

00:52:14.390 --> 00:52:16.300
stage one more time.

00:52:16.300 --> 00:52:18.830
Roger's drums kick in, an eight
bar count, and I'm in

00:52:18.830 --> 00:52:22.330
with him, the galloping groove
that started it all for me.

00:52:22.330 --> 00:52:26.380
30,000 California kids, eyes and
teeth smiling, cameras and

00:52:26.380 --> 00:52:30.240
cell phones popping, a million
tiny seductions all at once,

00:52:30.240 --> 00:52:32.500
and the music never
sounded better.

00:52:32.500 --> 00:52:33.233
Thank you.

00:52:33.233 --> 00:52:34.712
[APPLAUSE]

00:52:34.712 --> 00:52:36.684
ADAM STEWART: John.

00:52:36.684 --> 00:52:40.135
On behalf of Google, thank you
very much for doing this.

00:52:40.135 --> 00:52:43.100
That was really terrific.

00:52:43.100 --> 00:52:45.810
So John's going to be signing
books right outside.

00:52:45.810 --> 00:52:47.060
Thanks, everybody.

